  "texts": [
    "We define the number of tweets Y t,u,l made in week t by user u in language l. As tweets are count data, we model the Y t,u,l to follow a Poisson distribution with intensity λ t,u,l, where",
    "Here, μ is a general time-constant intercept, which captures the average tweet intensity over all users, languages and weeks.",
    "The W u,l are language-specific time-constant random intercepts for each user u, assumed to be normally distributed.",
    "They capture by how much the average tweeting behaviour (more or less tweets) of each user in each language differs from the general mean μ.",
    "Finally, s l (t) denotes a smooth global time trend for each language l (Ukrainian, Russian, English) and captures changes in the tweeting behaviour over all users over time."
  ],
